ng to music -- tOn why liars often tell the truth but not the reverse, and on whether habits can change -- tOn certain popular sayings -- tOn the distinction between different forms of divination -- tOn why there are four categories for inquiry: whether, what, which, and why -- tOn the nonexistent -- tOn why a physician rejoices at the recovery of his patient -- tOn why money is made of silver and gold and not other substances -- tOn the specific time when the soul attaches itself to the body -- tOn whether souls can recollect what they used to know after leaving the body -- tOn why mountains exist -- tOn why there are three souls -- tOn why the sea is located on a particular side of the earth -- tOn why seawater is salty -- tOn how we can see things in our sleep without an organ of sense perception -- tOn a puzzle concerning the possibility of seeking something we do not know -- tOn why it does not snow in the summer -- tOn the proof for the existence of angels -- tOn what justifies the suffering of children and non-rational animals -- tOn why it takes us longer to hear thunder than to see lightning -- tOn the possibility that a person may abandon every belief he adopts ad infinitum -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tFurther Reading -- tIndex -- tAbout the NYU Abu Dhabi Institute -- 00ttAbout the Typefaces -- tTitles Published by the Library of Arabic Literature -- tAbout the Editor–Translators0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aQuestions and answers from two great philosophersWhy is laughter contagious? Why do mountains exist? Why do we long for the past, even if it is scarred by suffering? Spanning a vast array of subjects that range from the philosophical to the theological, from the philological to the scientific, The Philosopher Responds is the record of a set of questions put by the litterateur Abu Hayyan al-Tawhidi to the philosopher and historian Abu 'Ali Miskawayh. Both figures were foremost contributors to the remarkable flowering of cultural and intellectual life that took place in the Islamic world during the reign of the Buyid dynasty in the fourth/tenth century. The correspondence between al-Tawhidi and Miskawayh holds a mirror to many of the debates and preoccupations of the time and reflects the spirit of rationalistic inquiry that animated their era. It also provides insight into the intellectual outlooks of two thinkers who were divided as much by their distinctive temperaments as by the very different trajectories of their professional careers. Alternately whimsical and tragic, wondering and brooding, trivial and profound, al-Tawhidi’s questions provoke an interaction as interesting in its spiritedness as in its content. This new edition of The Philosopher Responds is accompanied by the first full-length English translation of this important text, bringing this interaction to life for the English reader.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAuthors, ArabyTo 1258vCorrespondence. 0aIslamic philosophyvEarly works to 1800. 0aIslamic philosophy. 0aPhilosopherszIrany10th centuryvCorrespondence. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aMiskawayh, Abū ʿAlī, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMontgomery, James E.1 aOrfali, Bilal, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPomerantz, Maurice A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVasalou, Sophia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z97831107227270 cprintz978147983460040uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479865444.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479865444423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479865444/original  a978-3-11-